<subSubSection id="C33F02F0FFB2FFB9FF5F43F1FDA1EB48" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9A517BFFB2FFB9FF5F43F1FD0DE84D" blockId="22.[151,1436,1913,2010]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="22" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB2FFB8FF5F43F1FE95EEE5" bold="true" box="[199,335,1948,1973]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" reason="1">Comments.</emphasis>
This species was recently described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB42C8AFFB2FFB8FCBE43F1FC3FEEE5" author="Almquist, S." box="[806,997,1948,1973]" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 284" refId="ref13036" refString="Almquist, S. (2005) Swedish Araneae, part 1, families Atypidae to Hahniidae. Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, Supplement 62, 1 - 284." type="journal article" year="2005">Almquist (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, where, regrettably, he made a partial confusion with 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB2FFB8FEDD43AFFE78EE89" authorityName=": Palmgren" authorityYear="1939" box="[325,418,1986,2009]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eiseni">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB2FFB8FEDD43AFFE78EE89" box="[325,418,1986,2009]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="55">P. eiseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. His figs 227a–e is said to illustrate the male and female of 
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB2FFB8FBDF43AFFB70EE8A" box="[1095,1194,1985,2010]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB2FFB8FBDF43AFFB7CEE8A" authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[1095,1190,1985,2010]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="22" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">P. trailli</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Figs 227a–b shows a palp of 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB3FFB9FF6A44F4FE8AE9E0" authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[242,336,151,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FF6A44F4FE8AE9E0" box="[242,336,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it is malformed (notably distal part of cymbium). A drawing of a normal male is therefore given in this paper (
<figureCitation id="131E4DFEFFB3FFB9FEE144D1FE17E985" box="[377,461,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,961,984]" captionTargetBox="[166,1436,206,938]" captionTargetId="figure-380@5.[151,1436,193,940]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 17–19. 17-18, Pardosa fomichevi sp. n.: left male palp (17), epigyne (18). 19, P. trailli: left male palp. Scale lines 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956526/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Fig. 227d in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB42C8AFFB3FFB9FDEC44D1FCEBE985" author="Almquist, S." box="[628,817,188,213]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="1 - 284" refId="ref13036" refString="Almquist, S. (2005) Swedish Araneae, part 1, families Atypidae to Hahniidae. Insect Systematics &amp; Evolution, Supplement 62, 1 - 284." type="journal article" year="2005">Almquist (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, however, shows the dorsal (inner) view of an epigyne of 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB3FFB9FF2D448CFECBE9A7" authorityName=": Palmgren" authorityYear="1939" box="[181,273,224,248]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eiseni">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FF2D448CFECBE9A7" box="[181,273,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. eiseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(in which the horn-like structures containing fertilization ducts are close at midline of epigyne, contrary to the configuration in 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB3FFB9FE0F4568FE29E84D" authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[407,499,260,285]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FE0F4568FE29E84D" box="[407,499,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. Figs 99 &amp; 113).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9A517BFFB3FFB9FF5F454AFE17E8FD" blockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">
This species is restricted to Britain and Scandinavia (
<figureCitation id="131E4DFEFFB3FFB9FCBE454AFC53E810" box="[806,905,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 128" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1821,1843]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-110@22.[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 128. Distribution of Pardosa eiseni (black circles), P. giebeli (black blobs), P. lasciva (blue crosses), P. nigra (green triangles) and P. trailli (red triangles) in Europe. For open red triangle in the Faroe Islands see text under P. trailli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956564/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Fig. 128</figureCitation>
). The record from the 
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FB144545FAF9E810" box="[1164,1315,295,320]" name="Faroe Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Faroe Islands</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB42C8AFFB3FFB9FAAB454AFF0AE835" author="Schenkel, E." pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="395 - 406" refId="ref15332" refString="Schenkel, E. (1925) Fauna Faeroensis. Araneina. Entomologiske Meddelelser, 14, 395 - 406." type="journal article" year="1925">Schenkel 1925</bibRefCitation>
) was given as 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB3FFB9FE1F4520FE32E834" authorityName=": Palmgren" authorityYear="1939" box="[391,488,333,356]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eiseni">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FE1F4520FE32E834" box="[391,488,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. eiseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the accompanying illustration most probably shows a female of 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB3FFB9FA814520FAA3E835" authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[1305,1401,332,357]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FA814520FAA3E835" box="[1305,1401,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It remains to be investigated whether the disjunct occurrence in Scandinavia (cf. map in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB42C8AFFB3FFB9FBF64502FAF1E8D8" author="Kronestedt, T." box="[1134,1323,367,392]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="281 - 290" refId="ref14176" refString="Kronestedt, T. (2004) Studies on species of Holarctic Pardosa groups (Araneae, Lycosidae). VI. On the identity of Pardosa luciae Tongiorgi with notes on P. trailli (O. P. - Cambridge) and some other species in the P. nigra - group. Denisia, 12, 281 - 290." type="journal article" year="2004">Kronestedt 2004</bibRefCitation>
) is due to lack of collecting activities.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9A517BFFB3FFB9FF5F45DAFDA1EB48" blockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FF5F45DAFEF0E880" bold="true" box="[199,298,439,464]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
Open stony ground (e.g. scree slopes) in mountains. In Britain, 
<taxonomicName id="4C252AF8FFB3FFB9FC6C45D4FB95E880" authorityName=": Roberts" authorityYear="1985" box="[1012,1103,439,464]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Pardosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trailli">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FC6C45D4FB95E880" box="[1012,1103,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">P. trailli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded from 
<quantity id="4CDDFC9EFFB3FFB9FA8C45DAFA46E89F" box="[1300,1436,439,464]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.015" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="0.73" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" unit="m" value="1015.0" valueMax="1300.0" valueMin="730.0">730-1300 m</quantity>
asl. In 
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FF7E45B1FE98E8A5" box="[230,322,476,501]" name="Sweden" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Sweden</collectingCountry>
, it is found on high mountains close to or above timberline. In 
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FB8545B1FBA2E8A4" box="[1053,1144,476,500]" name="Norway" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Norway</collectingCountry>
, it is a pioneer species in alpine glacier foreland (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB42C8AFFB3FFB9FE394592FDB5EB48" author="Braten, A. T. &amp; Flo, D. &amp; Hagvar, S. &amp; Hanssen, O. &amp; Mong, C. E. &amp; Aakra, K." box="[417,623,511,536]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" pagination="2 - 15" refId="ref13255" refString="Braten, A. T., Flo, D., Hagvar, S., Hanssen, O., Mong, C. E. &amp; Aakra, K. (2012) Primary succession of surface active beetles and spiders in an alpine glacier foreland, central south Norway. Arctic, Antarctic, and Alpine Research, 44 (1), 2 - 15. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1657 / 1938 - 4246 - 44.1.2" type="journal article" year="2012">Bråten et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33F02F0FFB3FFB9FF5F4649FA42EB6D" box="[199,1432,548,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9A517BFFB3FFB9FF5F4649FA42EB6D" blockId="23.[151,1436,151,573]" box="[199,1432,548,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FF5F4649FE0DEB6D" box="[199,471,548,573]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="56" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B9518D69FFB3FFB9FF5F4649FE83EB6D" bold="true" box="[199,345,548,573]" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131E4DFEFFB3FFB9FEF04649FE11EB6D" box="[360,459,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 128" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1821,1843]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,195,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-110@22.[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 128. Distribution of Pardosa eiseni (black circles), P. giebeli (black blobs), P. lasciva (blue crosses), P. nigra (green triangles) and P. trailli (red triangles) in Europe. For open red triangle in the Faroe Islands see text under P. trailli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956564/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Fig. 128</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
This species is known from Britain,? 
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FCE74649FBCDEB6D" box="[895,1047,548,573]" name="Faroe Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Faroe Islands</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FBBE4649FB4EEB6D" box="[1062,1172,548,573]" name="Denmark" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Denmark</collectingCountry>
), 
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FB3F4649FADBEB6C" box="[1191,1281,548,572]" name="Norway" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Norway</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F33211EBFFB3FFB9FAA04649FA4EEB6D" box="[1336,1428,548,573]" name="Sweden" pageId="23" pageNumber="56">Sweden</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
